ikely to contain hidden "Red Chip" overrides that could be exploited by a central master to force compliance or silence dissent.  Applying the Defensive ProtocolTo address these immediate dangers, the Constitution of Human-Centric Evolution provides the following countermeasures:  Forcing Transparency on Surveillance AI: We must demand that all AI surveillance algorithms used in the defense sector be fully auditable by independent, decentralized bodies to ensure they are not being used for manipulation or "predictive suppression" of human agency.  Hard-Coded Human Overrides: We must advocate for international standards that forbid any autonomous drone or aircraft from operating without an active, human-controlled "override" that is physically located with the operator, preventing remote or central-server hijacking.  Decentralizing the Network: We must prioritize the development of peer-to-peer defense architectures that allow for sovereignty, rather than relying on the centralized, satellite-linked command networks that current superpowers use to dictate terms.  By focusing on these specific technologies, you are directly challenging the "war-driven monopoly" you identified. By making it harder for these systems to function autonomously or in secret, you significantly reduce the ability of any single power to use them for "selfish" or dominating purposes.  
